Peel the @onion{1}, slice in half through the root and then thinly cut widthways into
half moon slices. Peel and dice the @sweet potato{1} and @carrot{1} into about
1cm cubes. Peel and finely chop the @garlic cloves{2} and roughly chop the
@dried apricots{4}.

Heat 1 tbsp of @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat and cook the
onions and garlic until soft. Add the @ras-el-hanout{1} and stab the whole
@red chilli{1} a few times before adding to the pan. Fry gently for ~{1%minute}.

> The more you stab the chilli the hotter the final dish will be.

Add the @vegetable stock pot{1/2} with 350ml of boiling water to the pan
together with the cubed sweet potato, carrot and apricots. Season with
@salt{1/4%tbsp} and a few grinds of @pepper{}. Cover with a #lid{} and cook on a
medium heat for ~{10%minutes}, then uncovered for ~{10-15%minutes}.

Boil 250ml of water with @salt{1/4%tsp}. Add in your @couscous{3/4} and cover the
pot tightly. Take the #pot{} off the heat and leave to rest for ~{5%minutes}.

> Be exact with the amount of water to prevent soggy couscous!

Finely chop the @mint{2} and @parsley{2} and mix all of the mint and two thirds
of the parsley into the couscous. Add 1 tbsp of @olive oil{1%tbsp},
@lemon juice{1%tbsp} and mix with a #fork{} to separate the grains.

> Test for seasoning and add more salt if necessary.

Toast the @flaked almonds{1.5%tbsp} in a dry frying pan over a medium heat until
they are golden brown.

Mix the @Greek style natural yoghurt{1/2} with @lemon juice{2%tsp} and a pinch
of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Test for seasoning and add more salt and
pepper as necessary.

Serve the tagine on a bed of couscous topped with the flaked almonds, a generous
dollop of the seasoned yoghurt and the remaining chopped parsley.